Channel_Name: David Geffen School of Medicine UCLA
Description: people have been smoking for at least 7,000 years, but it wasn't until the 1800s that cigarettes became the smoke of choice, after machines were developed to mass produce them. 200 years later, in 2003, the electronic cigarette was invented in china. since then, the use of e-cigarettes, also known as vaping, has grown exponentially around the world.

Video_Title: JUUL, Vaping, and Electronic Cigarettes: A Public Health Crisis
Description: evidence continues to mount that e-cigarettes, including the widely popular juul devices, pose dangers to youths. in this session, presented by deepa camenga, md, faap, the most recent evidence on the health effects of e-cigarettes is reviewed. attendees also  learn techniques to screen teens for use of these products and how to counsel patients and parents. (monday, november 5, 2018)

Video_Title: Multi-Level Prevention Strategies to Address Teen E-Cigarette Use
Description: this webinar highlights the latest data trends, challenges in youth e-cigarette prevention, evidence-based tools and resources, and strategies for curbing e-cigarette use among youth. viewers will receive valuable information and resources to help address e-cigarette use among teens in their communities. presenters include prevention leaders from samhsa, the centers for disease control and prevention, the truth initiative, and the u.s. food and drug administration. find more resources and learn about samhsa’s national prevention week at samhsa.gov/prevention-week.

Video_Title: Health effects of Vaping and E-cigarette use, what is known thus far
Description:
before the hubbub over e-cigarette or vaping product use associated lung injury (evali), we had growing evidence that vaping would cause health problems. but how did this disease blow-up so fast? is it really vitamin e causing these cases of severe lung injury? we will discuss what is known and unknown about the effects of nicotine and thc containing e-cigarette aerosols on respiratory health, cardiovascular health, and neuro, renal and hepatic health while we are at it! outside of this acute disease entity (evali), what health effects are likely to occur due to vaping?

» laura crotty alexander, university of california at san diego
